---
import Primer from '../../layouts/Primer.astro';
import { url } from '../../lib/url';

const chapters = [
  {
    n: 'One',
    title: 'The Surface Beneath Everything',
    blurb: 'Almost every question in atomistic simulation is a question about one function — the energy of a set of atoms. Where it comes from, why the electrons make it expensive, and why a machine-learned potential is a cheap fit to it.',
    href: url('/primer/the-surface'),
  },
  {
    n: 'Two',
    title: 'Atoms as a Graph',
    blurb: 'How a function turns a pile of atoms into an energy: locality and the per-atom sum, the cutoff sphere, and the three symmetries a description must respect — why a molecule is not a list of coordinates.',
    href: url('/primer/atoms-as-a-graph'),
  },
  {
    n: 'Three',
    title: 'Inside the Network',
    blurb: 'Message passing and equivariance — the mechanism, drawn out the way the Illustrated Transformer draws attention.',
    href: url('/primer/inside-the-network'),
  },
  {
    n: 'Four',
    title: 'How One Gets Made',
    blurb: 'Datasets, the energy–force–stress loss, active learning, and what the word "foundation model" is doing in this field.',
    href: url('/primer/how-one-gets-made'),
  },
  {
    n: 'Five',
    title: 'At Inference Time',
    blurb: 'Relaxations, molecular dynamics, and what it means to serve one of these as a drop-in calculator in production.',
    href: url('/primer/at-inference-time'),
  },
  {
    n: 'Six',
    title: "What an MLIP Keeps — and Can't",
    blurb: 'A DFT calculation produces a whole electronic world; a potential keeps a thin slice. The three-tier carve between what you get for free, what you can reach if you ask, and what no energy model can ever give you.',
    href: url('/primer/what-mlips-keep'),
  },
];
---
<Primer
  title="How Matter Models Work"
  eyebrow="A Primer on Matter Models"
  deck="An illustrated walk from the quantum-mechanical bedrock up to the machine-learned interatomic potentials cataloged in this almanac — and an honest accounting of what they can and cannot do."
  byline="A working draft, written for one reader · 2026 Edition"
  gutter={false}
>
  <p class="lead">
    This is a side wing of the Almanac, not part of its catalog. The main book tells you
    <em>which</em> potentials exist and <em>where</em> they run. These pages try to explain
    <em>what they are</em> — building the idea up from the physics, the way one might explain
    a transformer by drawing every arrow rather than citing the paper. They are written for a
    reader who knows software and some machine learning but little chemistry — someone who has
    met names like MACE and UMA in the catalog and wants to know what they actually are.
  </p>

  <p>
    The method throughout is one plank at a time: lay something down, stand on it, lay the next —
    preferring a precise distinction to a tidy slogan, and saying plainly where the method runs
    out. All six chapters are drafted; the later ones are the freshest ink, so read them with a
    pencil.
  </p>

  <nav class="toc" aria-label="Chapters">
    {chapters.map((c) => (
      c.pending ? (
        <span class="toc-item pending">
          <span class="toc-num">Chapter {c.n}</span><span class="toc-soon">drafting</span>
          <div class="toc-title">{c.title}</div>
          <p class="toc-blurb">{c.blurb}</p>
        </span>
      ) : (
        <a class="toc-item" href={c.href}>
          <span class="toc-arrow" aria-hidden="true">→</span>
          <span class="toc-num">Chapter {c.n}</span>
          <div class="toc-title">{c.title}</div>
          <p class="toc-blurb">{c.blurb}</p>
        </a>
      )
    ))}
  </nav>

  <section class="sources" aria-label="Where to go from here">
    <span class="sources-label">where to go from here</span>
    <p style="font-size:14.5px; color:var(--ink-2); margin-bottom:0.8em;">
      The primer stops at a conceptual baseline. Depending on which thread you want to pull next:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Run a potential this afternoon</strong> — the <a class="ink-link" href="https://fair-chem.github.io">FAIR-chem docs</a> (home of UMA) and the <a class="ink-link" href="https://mace-docs.readthedocs.io">MACE docs</a> both have quickstarts; either drops into the <a class="ink-link" href="https://ase-lib.org">ASE</a> calculator slot of Chapter 5.</li>
      <li><strong>Compare the models</strong> — <a class="ink-link" href="https://matbench-discovery.materialsproject.org">Matbench Discovery</a> ranks the current crop against DFT references; the Almanac's own catalog tells you where each one runs.</li>
      <li><strong>Molecular dynamics, deeper</strong> — Abhishaike Mahajan's <a class="ink-link" href="https://www.owlposting.com/p/a-primer-on-molecular-dynamics">"A Primer on Molecular Dynamics"</a> is the accessible next read; Frenkel &amp; Smit's <em>Understanding Molecular Simulation</em> (3rd ed., 2023) is the standard text, written algorithm-first.</li>
      <li><strong>DFT, deeper</strong> — Sholl &amp; Steckel's <em>Density Functional Theory: A Practical Introduction</em> (2nd ed., 2022) is the gentlest real book on the subject; École Polytechnique's free <a class="ink-link" href="https://www.coursera.org/learn/density-functional-theory">Coursera course</a> if you prefer lectures.</li>
      <li><strong>The architectures</strong> — Duval et al.'s <a class="ink-link" href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2312.07511">"A Hitchhiker's Guide to Geometric GNNs"</a> maps every family Chapter 3 names, and the ones it doesn't.</li>
      <li><strong>Materials science from zero</strong> — Cambridge's <a class="ink-link" href="https://www.doitpoms.ac.uk">DoITPoMS</a> teaching packages cover crystals, bonding, and diffusion in short illustrated modules; for catalysis, start at the <a class="ink-link" href="https://opencatalystproject.org">Open Catalyst Project</a>.</li>
    </ul>
  </section>

  <p style="margin-top:2em; font-size:14px; color:var(--ink-3); font-family:var(--smallcaps); letter-spacing:0.08em; text-align:center;">
    <a class="ink-link" href={url('/')}>Return to the Almanac proper →</a>
  </p>
</Primer>
